characterises today’s British nationalism requires both recognition and theorisation. A meaningful understanding of new nationalism must reckon with the ideological range animating it and the deeply hostile aversion to different racial minorities that pervades its respective ideologies. Drawing on a variety of cultural and political themes – ranging from Corbyn’s dithering, the cult of Churchillism, the neoliberal fixation with a ‘point-system’ immigration policy, the muscular secularism of Richard Dawkins and friends, fears that the white working class have ‘become black’, and even simply the strange appeal of Harry Potter and Game of Thrones – this book provides a dazzling but always detailed study of how nationalism is the politics of today only because it is a politics of everything.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGreat BritainxRace relations. 0aNationalismzGreat Britain. 0aPopulismzGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aBrexit.  aChurchillism.  aGame of Thrones.  aGreat Britain.  aHarry Potter.  aJeremy Corbyn.  aNationalism.  aRichard Dawkins.  aanti-Establishment.  aimmigration.  apolitics.  aracial minorities.  aworking class.1 aValluvan, Sivamohan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612613940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526126139423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526126139/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles